author: The Associated Press
title: 5 Things to Know in Florida for Oct. 17
text:
5 Things to Know in Florida for Oct. 17 By The Associated Press -   
Your daily look at news, upcoming events and the stories that will be talked about today. 
NIELSEN SUES BUBBA THE LOVE SPONGE, SAYS HE TRIED TO TAMPER WITH RADIO SHOW RATINGS 
Among the allegations in the federal lawsuit filed Thursday: fraud; conspiracy to defraud; violating the Florida Deceptive and Unfair Practices Act; and interfering with business and contractual relations between Nielsen and Beasley, the company that owns the station that carries Clem’s show. 
2ND UNIVERSITY OF SOUTH FLORIDA FOOTBALL PLAYER ACCUSED OF FIRING A GUN ON CAMPUS 
University police arrested junior cornerback Lamar Robbins on Thursday. Police say they arrested Robbins after an investigation into the Oct. 11 arrest of freshman reserve offensive lineman Benjamin Knox. Arrest reports say Knox fired a gun at a dorm on the campus near Tampa. 
FLORIDA FIRES EMPLOYEE AT DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION FOR SCRUBBING SEAWORLD FROM STATE WEBSITE 
An animal rights group requested in September that the agency remove SeaWorld from its list of fun field trips and teacher discounts. Emails show that the issue was discussed among several officials including department attorneys. 
FIRE AT WAREHOUSE FILLED WITH FOOD ITEMS CAUSES MORE THAN $1 MILLION IN DAMAGE 
Officials say more than 60 firefighters eventually responded. Flames caused the roof and two of the exterior walls to collapse. The fire was under control by the middle of the afternoon. 
SKELETAL REMAINS FOUND IN AREA WHERE MAN TOLD DEPUTIES HE BURIED FORMER GIRLFRIEND 
The Manatee County Sheriff’s Office reports finding skeletal remains Friday morning in an area of Holmes Beach on Anna Maria Island where 45-year-old William Cumber led deputies Wednesday. Cumber pleaded no contest Thursday to the murder of Sabine Musel-Buehler.
